definition.value: A luteolin glucosiduronic acid consisting of luteolin having a beta-D-glucosiduronic acid residue attached at the 3'-position.
A luteolin glucosiduronic acid consisting of luteolin having a beta-D-glucosiduronic acid residue attached at the 5-position.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specifed as stearoyl and arachidonoyl respectively.
A triacyl-sn-glycerol in which the acyl groups at positions 1, 2 and 3 are specifed as stearoyl, arachidonoyl and oleoyl respectively.
An anthracyline cation that is the conjugate acid of carminomycin, obtained by protonation of the amino group.

A 2-[(dimethylamino)methyl]-1-(3-methoxyphenyl)cyclohexanol in which both stereocentres have S-configuration; the (S,S)-enantiomer of the racemic opioid analgesic tramadol, it exhibits ten-fold lower analgesic potency than the (R,R)-enantiomer.

A hydrochloride resulting from the reaction of (R,R)-tramadol with 1 molar equivalent of hydrogen chloride; the (R,R)-enantiomer of the racemic opioid analgesic tramadol hydrochloride, it exhibits ten-fold higher analgesic potency than the (S,S)-enantiomer.

A hydrochloride resulting from the reaction of (S,S)-tramadol with 1 molar equivalent of hydrogen chloride; the (S,S)-enantiomer of the racemic opioid analgesic tramadol hydrochloride, it exhibits ten-fold lower analgesic potency than the (R,R)-enantiomer.
A 1,3-diglyceride with both acyl groups specified as oleoyl.
A racemate consisting of equal amounts of (R,R)- and (S,S)-tramadol(1+).
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the tertiary amino group of (R,R)-tramadol.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the tertiary amino group of (S,S)-tramadol.
A flavanone glycoside that is (+)-taxifolin substituted by a beta-D-xylopyranosyl residue at position 3.
A flavanone glycoside that is (+)-taxifolin substituted by an alpha-L-arabinofuranosyl residue at position 3.
A flavanone glycoside that is (-)-taxifolin substituted by a beta-D-xylopyranosyl residue at position 3.
The pyranose form of any beta-D-arabinoside
A flavanone glycoside that is (+)-taxifolin substituted by a beta-D-arabinopyranosyl residue at position 3.
A flavanone glycoside that is (+)-epitaxifolin substituted by an alpha-D-arabinopyranosyl residue at position 3.
Any alpha-D-arabinoside existing in pyranose form
A flavanone glycoside that is (+)-taxifolin substituted by an alpha-D-arabinopyranosyl residue at position 3.
A taxifolin that has (2R,3S)-configuration.
A flavanone glycoside that is (-)-epitaxifolin substituted by an alpha-D-arabinopyranosyl residue at position 3.
A flavanone glycoside that is (+)-taxifolin substituted by an alpha-L-arabinopyranosyl residue at position 3.

A dihydropyridine that is 1,4-dihydropyridine which is substituted by methyl groups at positions 2 and 6, a (2-methoxyethoxy)carbonyl group at position 3, a m-nitrophenyl group at position 4, and an isopropoxycarbonyl group at position 5. An L-type calcium channel blocker, it acts particularly on cerebral circulation, and is used both orally and intravenously for the prevention and treatment of subarachnoid hemorrhage from ruptured intracranial aneurysm.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is isorhamnetin substituted at position 3 by a beta-D-glucosyl residue.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is isorhamnetin substituted at position 3 by a beta-D-galactosyl residue.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is isorhamnetin substituted at position 7 by a beta-D-glucosyl residue.
Members of the class of  glycolipid that are characteristic to the morning glory family, Convolvulaceae. They are high molecular weight oligosaccharide derivatives of hydroxylated fatty acids.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol in which the acyl group is specified as oleoyl.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is isorhamnetin substituted at position 3 by a beta-L-glucosyl residue.
Any L-glucoside having beta-configuration at its anomeric centre.
A hydrochloride obtained by combining nimustine with one equivalent of hydrochloric acid. An antineoplastic agent especially effective against malignant brain tumors.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is 3'-O-methyltricetin substituted by an alpha-L-rhamnopyranosyl residue at position 3.
Any  metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in eukaryotes, the taxon that include members of the fungi, plantae and animalia kingdoms.
Any eukaryotic metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in animals that include diverse creatures from sponges, insects to mammals.
Any animal metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in mammals.

Any member of the group of eight water-soluble vitamins originally thought to be a single compound (vitamin B) that play important roles in cell metabolism. The group comprises of vitamin B1, B2, B3, B5, B6, B7, B9, and B12 (Around 20 other compounds were once thought to be B vitamins but are no longer classified as such).
A racemate consisting of equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-nisoldipine. A calcium channel blocker, it is used in the treatment of hypertension and angina pectoris.
Any mammalian metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in a mouse (Mus musculus).
Any  fungal metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in Baker's yeast (Saccharomyces cerevisiae).
A glycosyloxyflavone that is isorhamnetin substituted at position 7 by a beta-L-glucosyl residue.
Any galactoside having L-configuration.
Any L-galactoside having beta-configuration at its anomeric centre.
Any L-galactoside having alpha-configuration at its anomeric centre.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is isorhamnetin substituted at position 3 by a beta-L-galactosyl residue.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is isorhamnetin substituted at position 4' by a beta-L-glucosyl residue.
A mixture containing all eight of the B vitamins (B1, B2, B3, B5, B6, B7, B9, and B12). It is used as a dietary supplement and as a component of growth media for microorganisms.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is isorhamnetin substituted at position 4' by a beta-D-glucosyl residue.
